{"source_key":"sha256-ea08d35f42d5530fbe92c80d4f5b27e9","record_index":354,"record_hash":"sha256:a5dfa5df1f22230a961aac20342087ac680509ba8097bdf76fae9a72910ffdb1","timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:34:43.211Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 68f2d2\nWall time: 0.0000 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 1397\nOutput:\n- short term production: depend on the GitButler repository as a pinned Cargo\n  git dependency and import the `but-agentlog` package\n- if the full GitButler workspace dependency graph is too heavy, split a smaller\n  `but-agentlog-read` or `but-agenttrail-core` crate that owns target\n  construction, verified lookup, match reasons, and public projections\n\nExample shape:\n\n```toml\nbut-agentlog = { git = \"https://github.com/gitbutlerapp/gitbutler.git\", rev = \"<pinned-revision>\", package = \"but-agentlog\" }\n```\n\nThe important rule is no copied reader logic. Forge may own Agent Trail\nsnapshot, visibility, and UI policy, but the canonical storage interpretation\nshould stay in `but-agentlog`.\n\n## Node/Rust Boundary\n\nGitButler already has a working NAPI pattern:\n\n- `crates/but-api` marks Rust APIs with `#[but_api(napi)]`\n- `crates/but-napi` is a `cdylib` that links the generated exports\n- `packages/but-sdk` runs `@napi-rs/cli`, ships generated `index.js`,\n  `index.d.ts`, and platform `.node` artifacts, and exposes typed functions to\n  Electron's main process\n\nAgent Trail should borrow the packaging shape, not the whole desktop API\nsurface. Do not make Forge depend on the broad `@gitbutler/but-sdk` package just\nto read agent logs; it brings unrelated workspace, mutation, legacy, and desktop\nconcepts into a server feature that should stay narrow.\n\nThe preferred Forge-side boundary is:\n\n```text\nNext route/API -> TypeScript AgentTrail service -> dedicated Agent Trail NAPI package\n```\n\nGood package shape:\n\n```text\ncrates/agent-trail-napi or crates/but-agenttrail-napi\npackages/agent-trail-sdk or packages/but-agenttrail-sdk\n```\n\nThe native package should expose one small server-only function first:\n\n```text\nprojectAgentTrail(request) -> AgentTrailProjection\n```\n\nThe request should contain the prepared repo path or GitMeta source, resolved\nmetadata OID, PR facts, limits, and projection version. The response should be\nonly\n[TRUNCATED]\nernal snapshot id\n- fork PRs are unsupported\n- Forge does not implement an extra public redaction layer\n- Forge should not shell out to `but agentlog`; add a public `but-agentlog`\n  library API or smaller read/projection crate plus a dedicated NAPI package\n  before public rendering\n\n## Ready For Build\n\nThe product direction is clear enough to start, but the UI is blocked on the\ndata contract. The first build should start with the load-bearing API boundary:\n\n1. add the `but-agentlog` public/read projection API or split a smaller\n   read/projection crate\n2. make that API accept PR facts and return allowlisted Agent Trail projection\n   data\n3. prove the redaction, bounds, match reasons, and drill-down handles with\n   fixtures\n4. add a dedicated Agent Trail NAPI package, following the `but-napi` /\n   `but-sdk` generated-artifact pattern, that wraps the API for Node\n5. build the Forge TypeScript API route, GitHub lookup, metadata fetch/cache\n   path, and snapshot generation against that native package\n6. build the page UI against the API route\n\nDo not start by rendering raw `but-agentlog` CLI output in Forge. That would\nskip the main safety boundary in this design.\n\n## Implementation Boundary\n\nKeep the capture/storage primitive boring. Put public review-facing projection\nlogic in a narrow read/projection API or a smaller crate layered above the\nstorage internals.\n\n`but-agentlog` owns:\n\n- capture\n- redaction\n- GitMeta storage\n- verified related-session lookup\n- compact local skim/read primitives\n- public/read projection primitives for Agent Trail\n- bounded exact record reads through opaque handles\n\nAgent Trail owns:\n\n- PR/review entry point\n- URL and snapshot flow\n- public-repository access checks\n- TypeScript orchestration in Forge\n- dedicated server-only NAPI package packaging for Forge\n- Rust helper process packaging only as a fallback if native addon deployment is\n  blocked\n- review-specific ranking\n- page layout and copy\n- share-specific presentation over the public projection\n- optional generated summaries\n","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-24T15:34:43.211Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}